============================================================
SECTION A: K-MEANS CLUSTERING PROBLEM STATEMENTS
============================================================

Common methodology used for all K-means tasks:
- Business objective and constraints identified.
- Data cleaning and preprocessing performed.
- Categorical variables converted to numeric (one-hot) for mixed datasets.
- Data scaled before clustering.
- Optimum K selected using scree/elbow support and silhouette score.
- Clusters validated using hierarchical clustering and ARI.

------------------------------------------------------------
A1) Airlines Dataset (EastWestAirlines)
------------------------------------------------------------
Business Objective:
Segment airline customers by mileage behavior and rewards usage.

Dataset Info:
- Source: EastWestAirlines (1) (1).xlsx (sheet: data)
- Shape: 3999 x 12
- Features used: Balance, Qual_miles, cc1_miles, cc2_miles, cc3_miles,
  Bonus_miles, Bonus_trans, Flight_miles_12mo, Flight_trans_12,
  Days_since_enroll, Award?
- Dropped ID: ID#

Model Results:
- Best K: 6
- KMeans silhouette: 0.3334
- Hierarchical silhouette: 0.3193
- ARI (KMeans vs Hierarchical): 0.8083
- KMeans cluster sizes: {0:1253, 1:2484, 2:143, 3:43, 4:15, 5:61}

Inference:
- Large segment with low miles and low award behavior.
- Separate segment with high balance/bonus and higher award likelihood.
- Niche high-value flyers exist (small but premium behavior clusters).

------------------------------------------------------------
A2) Crime Dataset (crime_data)
------------------------------------------------------------
Business Objective:
Group states with similar crime patterns for policy planning.

Dataset Info:
- Source: crime_data (1).xlsx
- Shape: 50 x 5
- Features used: Murder, Assault, UrbanPop, Rape
- Dropped: state name column `Unnamed: 0`

Model Results:
- Best K: 2
- KMeans silhouette: 0.4085
- Hierarchical silhouette: 0.4048
- ARI (KMeans vs Hierarchical): 0.9199
- KMeans cluster sizes: {0:30, 1:20}

Cluster Means (KMeans):
- Cluster 0: Murder 4.87, Assault 114.43, Rape 15.94
- Cluster 1: Murder 12.17, Assault 255.25, Rape 29.17

Inference:
- Cluster 1 represents comparatively high-crime states.
- Cluster 0 has moderate/low crime profile.

------------------------------------------------------------
A3) Insurance Policy Dataset
------------------------------------------------------------
Business Objective:
Create customer groups based on premium, age, claims, and income.

Dataset Info:
- Source: Insurance Dataset.xlsx
- Shape: 100 x 5
- Features: Premiums Paid, Age, Days to Renew, Claims made, Income

Model Results:
- Best K: 2
- KMeans silhouette: 0.3970
- Hierarchical silhouette: 0.3886
- ARI (KMeans vs Hierarchical): 0.7579
- KMeans cluster sizes: {0:75, 1:25}

Cluster Means (KMeans):
- Cluster 0: lower premium, younger average age, lower claims and income
- Cluster 1: higher premium, older age, higher claims and income

Inference:
- Natural split into standard-value and high-value/high-claim policy groups.

------------------------------------------------------------
A4) Telecom Mixed Dataset
------------------------------------------------------------
Business Objective:
Find telecom customer segments and derive possible churn-related insights.

Dataset Info:
- Source: Telco_customer_churn (1) (1).xlsx
- Shape: 7043 x 30
- Missing values: 5403 (handled with imputation)
- ID removed: Customer ID, Count
- Mixed data: categorical + numerical
- One-hot encoding used for categorical variables.

Model Results:
- Best K: 2
- KMeans silhouette: 0.2170
- Hierarchical silhouette: 0.1669
- ARI (KMeans vs Hierarchical): 0.5009
- KMeans cluster sizes: {0:4636, 1:2407}

KMeans segment profile (means):
- Cluster 0: Tenure 20.31, Monthly Charge 51.84, Total Charges 879.40
- Cluster 1: Tenure 55.65, Monthly Charge 89.65, Total Charges 4978.74

Inference:
- Two major groups: low-tenure/low-revenue vs high-tenure/high-revenue users.
- Longer tenure and bundled services indicate stronger retention tendency.

------------------------------------------------------------
A5) AutoInsurance Mixed Dataset
------------------------------------------------------------
Business Objective:
Segment auto insurance customers using mixed demographic/policy data.

Dataset Info:
- Source: AutoInsurance (1).xlsx
- Shape: 9134 x 24
- ID dropped: Customer
- Date encoded: Effective To Date (ordinal)
- One-hot encoding on categorical columns.

Model Results:
- Best K: 2
- KMeans silhouette: 0.0831
- Hierarchical silhouette: 0.1604
- ARI (KMeans vs Hierarchical): 0.0497
- KMeans cluster sizes: {0:3820, 1:5314}

KMeans profile (means):
- Cluster 0: Income 13232.78, CLV 9528.29, Total Claim Amount 641.95
- Cluster 1: Income 55215.15, CLV 6909.87, Total Claim Amount 284.67

Inference:
- Segments indicate separation by income and claim burden.
- Low silhouette suggests more complex sub-structure; additional feature engineering can improve segmentation.

------------------------------------------------------------
Benefits/Impact of K-Means Solutions:
------------------------------------------------------------
- Helps businesses identify homogeneous customer/state groups.
- Improves targeting, risk planning, retention strategy, and policy design.
- Supports data-driven intervention for high-risk or high-value segments.


============================================================
SECTION B: PCA PROBLEM STATEMENT (HEART DISEASE)
============================================================

Business Objective:
A pharmaceutical company needs patient segmentation based on age and clinical factors to support high-level insights for heart disease study.

Dataset Info:
- Source: heart disease.xlsx
- Shape: 303 x 14
- Missing values: 0
- Target distribution: {1:165, 0:138}

Preprocessing:
- Used 13 predictor features for unsupervised clustering.
- Excluded target from clustering model input.
- Applied standard scaling.

K-Means on Original Data:
- Best K: 2
- Original KMeans silhouette: 0.1682
- Original Hierarchical silhouette: 0.1325

PCA:
- Extracted first 3 principal components: PC1, PC2, PC3
- Explained variance ratio: [0.2125, 0.1182, 0.0941]
- Cumulative variance (3 PCs): 0.4248
- New dataset created: heart_pca_3_components.csv

Clustering on PCA Data (K=2):
- PCA KMeans silhouette: 0.3376
- PCA Hierarchical silhouette: 0.2897

Before vs After PCA Comparison:
- ARI (KMeans original vs PCA): 0.9474 (high similarity)
- ARI (Hierarchical original vs PCA): 0.3771

Conclusion:
- K=2 is the optimal cluster count.
- PCA with 3 components preserves KMeans cluster structure well.
- Clustering quality improves after PCA in this dataset.

Benefits/Impact:
- Faster and simpler analysis with reduced dimensions.
- Better patient stratification and interpretability for medical insight generation.
- Supports treatment study planning by identifying major patient groups.

